    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-01-24T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-01-24T18:00:00-05:00" n="311"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d311">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 658.119/180a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-01-24T18:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 24, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6345. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName> [from
                    War Trade Board]:</p>
                <p>No. 35. Your No. 50. Terms of proposal to Sweden noted. If this proposal is
                    accepted we desire to maintain the principle already agreed upon of equal
                    division of neutral tonnage between United States and Great Britain. The <hi
                        rend="italic">Österland</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Jemtland</hi> would be
                    excepted from the operation of this principle as the disposition of these ships
                    is specifically dealt with by proposals. We are, however, willing that the
                    United States’ share of tonnage be contributed to make up the 100,000 tons to be
                    devoted temporarily to the needs of France and Italy and to save time now agree
                    to leave in England’s hands the allocation of our share of this tonnage to
                    France and Italy—for not exceeding period of 60 days. Cable how it is divided,
                    giving names of ships.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PFL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
